metadata.name: Word-eating worms #50
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork.

An old letter recounts the problems and feelings caused by woodworms: worms known to eat not only the beams and wood of houses, but also old books. As an analogy to this daily occurrence, emoticons appear and with the good spirit of simplifying they begin to gnaw away so much literary flourish.

The piece puts in counterpoint two forms of communication: emoticons and traditional writing. Here an inevitable contrast is sought between the standardization of the feelings of emojis, and the excessive flourishes of texts, possibly already from other times.

Original flute (tap & frullato), cello (pizz) and marimba samplers.
((click to start sound))

[s] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)

metadata.name: Pipeline #24
metadata.description:
The only way to deal with an unfree world is to become so absolutely free that your very existence is an act of rebellion. 
[Albert Camus]

I imagined a pipeline that runs within the limits of a three-dimensional cube. Each segment takes an arbitrary direction from time to time, careful not to cross the limits and not to occupy non-free spaces.
It can happen, quite rarely, that the pipeline has no more spaces available... and then the iteration stops, giving rise to a relatively simple structure.
You can follow the pipeline path by interactively manipulating the point of view.

metadata.name: Alleles #115
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Cursory examination of the genetic information presented suggests subject may develop a psychological profile prone to frequent periods of greed and psychological projection, yet also posesses an aptitude for above average interpersonal communication and analytical skills. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 216-222cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 119-127 years.

metadata.name: Through the Maze #38
metadata.description:
Constructing the pillars of life
Sculpted with fragments of time
Written on parchments of sky
Revealing the poetry of the gods

Between congruent representations of time
Exists a gap of complex irreverent forms
An anarchy of the body and the senses
Lying between the absurd and the sublime.

Project created using fractal art + code + chaos theory to generate unusual structures and geometries within fractals.

metadata.name: Rebug #141
metadata.description:
A debug view of the underlying particulate algorithm of Atoms' Gaze and Quantum Folly. Refined as a gift for collectors.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-08-06 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Arches #30
metadata.description:
'Arches' explores the connection between a dynamic artificial structure and an algorithm that mimics the behaviour of a living organism, the Physarum slime mold.

Use your mouse to explore the scene (zooming, panning).

Press 's' to save an image.
Press 'r' to rotate the camera.
Press 'd' to show debug interface

Further you can play with the algorithm settings (shown in console):

Press 't' to increase decay
Press 'g' to decrease decay
Press 'y' to increase deposit
Press 'h' to decrease deposit
Press 'u' to increase mutation strength
Press 'j' to decrease mutation strength
Press 'i' to increase point size
Press 'k' to decrease point size
Press 'o' to increase eating
Press 'l' to decrease eating

Code licensed under NFTL 1.0. Some code has been reused from nicoptere's physarum, which is licensed under the Unlicensed license. Some of ciphrd's Microcosm work was utilized too, under special personal license from ciphrd.

metadata.name: Patched with Tartan #25
metadata.description:
Patched with Tartan is a generative patchwork made with p5.js. 
Evolving from my earlier work, "Patched", this new piece has 576 possible layout combinations, 17 new printed patterns on a choice of 7 new textile textures and two new woven fabrics with near infinite colour variation chosen from one of 13 palettes. 

This piece introduces a new tartan fabric which gives it its name. Due to the vagaries of generative art it is quite possible that a piece won't contain any tartan though so all holders of Patched with Tartan will receive free access to a brand new pure tartan token in a couple of weeks.

'2' to regenerate at 2000x2000
'3' to regenerate at 3000x3000
'r' to regenerate at window size

metadata.name: Zephyr #113
metadata.description:
The name Zephyr traces back to Zephyrus, the Greek god of the west wind, and refers to any light breeze. The flowing particles get pushed around by a zephyr, creating interesting and organic patterns.

Live Mode Controls:

- Default is 2000x2000 pixel canvas. Press “1” for 1000x1000px canvas, “3” for 3000x3000px, “4” for 4000x4000px
- Press 'p' to save a png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js
